article.description:
Marcelus Kemp scored 25 points and Nick
Fazekas added 20 to lead Nevada to a 70-59 win over New
Mexico State in the semifinals of the Western Athletic Conference
tournament Friday night.
article.headline: No. 24 Nevada surges past New Mexico State
article.linkText: No. 24 Nevada surges past New Mexico State
article.story: RENO, Nev. (AP) -- With the big men mixing it up inside, Nevada's Marcelus Kemp did most of his damage from the outside. Kemp made four 3-pointers and scored 25 points to lead the Wolf Pack (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today; No. 21 AP) to their 13th straight win, 70-59 over New Mexico State in the semifinals of the Western Athletic Conference tournament Friday night. Nick Fazekas added 20 points and seven rebounds and Ramon Sessions had nine assists for the Wolf Pack (26-5), who scored seven straight points in the final 2 minutes to extend the second-longest winning streak in the NCAA behind Gonzaga's 18. "Coach was calling the plays and I was making my shots," said Kemp, a sophomore who sat out last season with an injury but shot 8-for-15 from the field. Elijah Ingram had 17 points and seven rebounds and David Fisher scored 10 for New Mexico State (16-14) in a physical game in which the Aggies fought back from a 10-point deficit at halftime to tie the game at 46 midway through the second half. Fisher was thrown out of the game for a flagrant technical and Aggies coach Reggie Theus had to be restrained by his assistants as he went after a referee in the closing minute. "The referee said (Fisher) threw a punch," Theus said after the game. "It's a bonehead move if he did it. I didn't see it." Nevada, which is 16-1 at home this season, advanced to the finals Saturday against Utah State (23-7), which beat Louisiana Tech 68-64 in the other semifinal. Nevada's last loss was at home on Jan. 23 against Utah State, 59-53. "We played well in spurts and didn't play well at times. Often games in March aren't pretty, but we were able to find a way to win," said Nevada coach Mark Fox, whose team won the regular season WAC title for the third year in a row and is bidding for its third straight trip to the NCAA tournament. In addition to Fisher, New Mexico State lost starting power forward Tyrone Nelson early in the second half to a hand injury. "It was a heck of a ballgame. I obviously don't like the way it ended up. I thought it was lopsided in a couple of ways," Theus said. "Elijah Ingram probably got fouled 50 times tonight and he went to the line six times. The reason I'm so proud of these guys is they never give up. They fight no matter what is going on. We lost two of our starters in the second half and they still tied it up." With Nevada leading 38-28 at the half, Fisher scored 10 points during a 16-6 run to start the second half and tie the score at 44. However, Fisher was ejected a minute later for throwing a missed punch at Fazekas, and Kemp made both free throws to put Nevada ahead 46-44 with 10:49 to go. Ingram's free throws tied it at 46, but DeMarshay Johnson and Mo Charlo each converted three-point plays and Charlo added two more free throws in an 8-2 run to put Nevada ahead 54-48 with 6:48 left. After Ingram made a pair of free throws, Fazekas converted another three-point play to make it 57-50. Lawrence dunked off a rebound to pull to 57-52 but Kemp's 3-pointer made it 60-52. Ingram's 3-pointer cut the lead to 63-55 with 2:25 to go. But Fazekas made two free throws, Kemp drove for a basket and then hit a 3-pointer for a 70-55 lead with just over a minute left. Fazekas scored 12 points in the first 4½ minutes, including two 3s and a slam dunk, and Johnson made a left-handed scoop shot to put Nevada ahead 16-8 at 14:21. Kevin Ford followed Ingram's 3-pointer with a dunk to pull within 19-13. But Charlo and Kemp hit 3-pointers on a 10-2 run capped by Johnson's dunk to push the lead to 29-15. Nevada led 38-28 at the half. After sitting out last year with a knee injury, Kemp is Nevada's second-leading scorer averaging 14.1 points. He is shooting 44-for-128 (35 percent) from 3-point range. "He's just grown so much from the time he came here and from the time he was a freshman," Fox said. "He's fought through a lot of adversity. He's starting to feel comfortable and healthy and therefore he can be aggressive and that is probably the key." Fox said the league title game will be a big test for Nevada. "Utah State is a terrific basketball team," he said. "They have no weakness. They are terrific defensively in both their defenses. They are a great offensive team. They are a terrific 3-point shooting team. There is a reason they have as many wins as they do."
